Namaste,\n&gt; \n&gt; I do n=\r\not want to drag this on, but these are crucial points.\n&gt; \n&gt; &gt; If one profes=\r\nses to have knowledge he cannot do actions, for actions \n&gt; &gt; are worldly. T=\r\nhe atman is entirely opposed to action\n&gt; \n&gt; First of all, note one fact. Lo=\r\nng after becoming a sannyasin, Swami \n&gt; Sivananda travelled the world, wrot=\r\ne books, gave lectures and founded \n&gt; Divine Life Society, among other &quot;act=\r\nions&quot;! :-)\n&gt; \n&gt; *        *        *\n&gt; \n&gt; If he established DLS with the exp=\r\nectation that it becomes a success or \n&gt; 10,000 people join it or some such=\r\n thing, then it would become an \n&gt; ignorant action, i.e. action with attach=\r\nment. If he did the action \n&gt; completely ready for any outcome and without =\r\na sense of ownership, and \n&gt; as an instrument of the divine will, then it i=\r\ns neither &quot;worldly&quot; nor \n&gt; binding nor ignorant. The problem is not &quot;action=\r\ns&quot;, but actions with \n&gt; attachment and a sense of ownership, i.e. actions d=\r\nriven by the will and \n&gt; agenda of a limited ego.\n&gt; \n&gt; Actions should not b=\r\ne spoken ill of like this. Detached action is a \n&gt; *sacred duty* of every b=\r\neing. Gods and rishis came back again and again \n&gt; to earth to engage in de=\r\ntached action.\n&gt; \n&gt; *        *        *\n&gt; \n&gt; If &quot;the atman is entirely oppo=\r\nsed to action&quot;, then why is atman (Self) \n&gt; even allowing action? Why doesn=\r\n&#39;t it simply halt everything? Or, is all \n&gt; the action happening outside of=\r\n atman? Is there anything outside of \n&gt; atman at all?\n&gt; \n&gt; Some buddhist ph=\r\nilosophies coined the term anatman (non-Self) to \n&gt; describe transient thin=\r\ngs. But, in Vedic philosophy, there is no \n&gt; anatman. All that is is atman =\r\n(Self). Ocean is permanent and still, but \n&gt; ripples that arise in it are t=\r\nransient and moving. But ripples are part \n&gt; of ocean only and you do not s=\r\ntart labeling ripples as &quot;non-ocean&quot;.\n&gt; \n&gt; Atman or Purusha or Shiva is the=\r\n potential energy of this cosmos, while \n&gt; Maya or Prakriti or Shakti is th=\r\ne kinetic energy of this cosmos. Shiva \n&gt; and Shakti are seen as different =\r\nentities by some people, but rishis \n&gt; have declared their oneness. Potenti=\r\nal energy becomes kinetic energy and \n&gt; vice versa.\n&gt; \n&gt; Atman is the still=\r\n ocean and Maya is the force (kinetic) that gives rise \n&gt; to moving ripples=\r\n on the surface. A ripple that exerts itself to move in \n&gt; a particular way=\r\n keeps colliding with the force and keeps moving hither \n&gt; and tither in a =\r\nchaotic way for a very long time. A ripple that does not \n&gt; exert itself an=\r\nd moves smoothly as dictated by the force will eventually \n&gt; grind to a hal=\r\nt and cease to exist as a ripple on the surface. It then \n&gt; becomes part of=\r\n the still ocean. If a ripple exerts itself to become \n&gt; still, it may even=\r\n take longer to become still. What prolongs a ripple \n&gt; is not movement but=\r\n resisting the direction given by the force and \n&gt; exerting to move in a pa=\r\nrticular way (or even exerting to become still). \n&gt; A ripple that surrender=\r\ns to the force will ride the course and die down \n&gt; faster.\n&gt; \n&gt; Contemplat=\r\ne the imagery I presented above regarding Atman and Maya, \n&gt; ignorant/egois=\r\ntic action and detached action! It is very apt.\n&gt; \n&gt; *        *        *\n&gt; =\r\n\n&gt; In not-so-distant past, sannyasins remained in ashrams and isolated \n&gt; t=\r\nhemselves from society and did their sadhana. Swami Vivekananda started \n&gt; =\r\na new trend.\n&gt; \n&gt; A sannyasin renounces expectation of things from people s=\r\ntuck in \n&gt; transient material world and does not depend on anyone. But he m=\r\nay still \n&gt; *give* basic material things to those hapless people stuck in t=\r\nransient \n&gt; material world! For example, Swami Vivekananda and his brother =\r\nmonks \n&gt; went to places struck by plague, floods, droughts, cyclones etc an=\r\nd \n&gt; served people. They provided food, medicines etc (instead of lecturing=\r\n \n&gt; that body is a transient illusion and one should stop worrying about it=\r\ns \n&gt; welfare!) and also did construction work. They ignored the welfare of =\r\n\n&gt; their own bodies, put themselves at risk and overcame maya personally. \n=\r\n&gt; But they served those still stuck in maya without looking down upon them =\r\n\n&gt; or their needs or maya that trapped them! Those who wanted food got \n&gt; f=\r\nood, those who wanted medicines got medicines and those who wanted \n&gt; books=\r\n got books. Renunciation means you do not expect anything from \n&gt; anyone an=\r\nd accept whatever comes to you naturally. It does not \n&gt; necessarily mean r=\r\nejecting or ignoring others. Overcoming maya does not \n&gt; require belittling=\r\n maya or belittling those still stuck in maya.\n&gt; \n&gt; The trend started by Sw=\r\nami Vivekananda was continued by Swami Sivananda. \n&gt; For that reason, it is=\r\n a bit weird to see him talking so ill of action! \n&gt; He was obviously tryin=\r\ng to inspire a specific group of people for a \n&gt; specific body of work. The=\r\nse words are neither universal nor do they \n&gt; reflect his tremendous wisdom=\r\n I have seen elsewhere!\n&gt; \n&gt; *        *        *\n&gt; \n&gt; All this intellectual=\r\n discussion may be satisfying to some, but the \n&gt; quote from Swami Brahmana=\r\nnanda in the other mail is very apt: &quot;You have \n&gt; been only hearing of all =\r\nthese spiritual things. Now realise them. You \n&gt; have done enough study and=\r\n reasoning. Now do some spiritual practice. \n&gt; First take up that aspect of=\r\n God which appeals to you most. Follow your \n&gt; own path of Sadhana. When yo=\r\nu realise God through it, you will feel the \n&gt; joy of realising Him also in=\r\n other aspects and through other paths.&quot;\n&gt; \n&gt; According to Ramakrishna, Swa=\r\nmi Brahmananda was a gopala who accompanied \n&gt; Lord Krishna in a previous l=\r\nife. His words are simple, pragmatic and \n&gt; powerful.\n&gt; \n&gt; I want this foru=\r\nm to facilitate exchange of Vedic knowledge (and I will \n&gt; also be contribu=\r\nting, though in spurts). But I want more that this forum \n&gt; should inspire =\r\npeople to do sadhana and find God. In the end, that is \n&gt; what matters.\n&gt; \n=\r\n&gt; Best regards,\n&gt; Narasimha\n&gt; ---------------------------------------------=\r\n-------------\n&gt;    Free Jyotish Software, Free Jyotish Lessons, Jyotish Wri=\r\ntings,\n&gt; &quot;Do It Yourself&quot; ritual manuals for short Homam and Pitri Tarpana:=\r\n\n&gt; http://www.VedicAstrologer.org\n&gt;       Films that make a difference: htt=\r\np://SaraswatiFilms.org\n&gt;       Spirituality: http://groups.yahoo.com/group/=\r\nvedic-wisdom\n&gt;    Jyotish writings: http://groups.yahoo.com/group/JyotishWr=\r\nitings\n&gt;                       Twitter ID: @homam108\n&gt; --------------------=\r\n--------------------------------------\n&gt; \n&gt; On Mon, Jun 20, 2011 at 2:31 PM=\r\n, Krishnendu wrote:\n&gt; \n&gt;      Some may say: =C3=A2From. this it follows tha=\r\nt it is not necessary for \n&gt; a knower even to serve his preceptor or to per=\r\nform tapas.=C3=A2 \n&gt; Householders who are afraid of begging for bread and a=\r\nre afraid of \n&gt; ridicule argue like this through their sharp intelligence. =\r\nYou cannot \n&gt; say that even begging for bread is a binding rule on a sannya=\r\nsin. That \n&gt; is not a desire and the sannyasin is virtually a mendicant wit=\r\nhout rules \n&gt; binding him. He is not liable to any kind of command. Even on=\r\ne who does \n&gt; not know Brahman but who is desirous of emancipation should e=\r\nnter into \n&gt